description: Common Blue Violet, whatever that's going by. Looks like there may have been a lot of lumping going on recently in violet taxonomy -- if there's a botanist out there who can shed light, by all means do! My old Golden Guide says "lots of species, ID difficult because lots of hybridization." And it gives this one as V. sororia, Woolly Blue Violet. But my flower looked distinctly, suspiciously unwoolly, so I did a search. biology.smsu.edu/Herbarium/Plants of the Interior Highlands/Flowers/Viola sororia.jpg shows a plant that is comparably glabrous, so I think I've got the right animal. But www.nps.gov/plants/pubs/chesapeake/plant/2039.htm suggests that that species was lumped with V. papilionacea. plants.usda.gov also lumps them under V. sororia. So that's what I'm going with.
I think this is a white variant (or hybrid) of Common Blue Violet, Viola sororia, but honestly, I'm ready to give up on identifying violets!  Pretty, whatever it is.

The next photo shows the small plant's low growing structure. Note the short stems for the leaves, and longer stems for flowers. This raises flowers so pollinators will notice them. This plant is herbaceous.

The next photo shows a close up of the leaf. It is heart shaped with netted veination.

The last photo shows a long taproot. Dicots have central taproots, as opposed to monocots which have a fibrous root system.

description: Lavender blue, dilly dilly...that familiar rhyme came to mind after I researched this charming purple flower and found it was the common violet!  I saw scores of these blooms lining the shaded portion of the Tipton Trail path in a wet  and wooded area.  Illinois Wildflowers' website notes the common violet truly is common in our state of Illinois as it can be found in EVERY county (http://www.illinoiswildflowers.info/savanna/plants/cm_violet.htm).  Apparently I have a knack for finding edible plants as this sweet violet's blooms can be washed and used as a lovely, consumable decoration for foods - as stated on the same website.  If you live in Illinois, just step outside your door and you should be able to find some violets nearby.  Enjoy the search - it's a beautiful time of year!

I found these violets while taking a walk in a neighborhood. I found them in the grass and they were spread evenly throughout. They were easy for me to spot with their bright purple flowers protruding from the ground. You can find these flowers pretty much anywhere with grass in Bloomington/Normal and most people consider them to be weeds. Violets are a type of wildflower common throughout Illinois and often take residence in an environment with part sun/part shade and rich, silty loam. They are known to have five petaled-flowers with two upper leaves and two lower leaves that can turn from dark green to yellow/green depending on weather conditions. These flowers are usually not bothered by most bugs, but can attract bees from time to time (John Hilty, 2017). 

Information retrieved from: http://www.illinoiswildflowers.info/savanna/plants/cm_violet.htm

This small plant was found on the side of a hiking trail, with three flower blooms present. Violets usually bloom in early spring and can sometimes bloom again in fall because of their early blooming periods. Identifiers of the plant can include the heart-shaped leaves or the bright violet color of the flowers (hence the name).

Common blue violets can typically be found throughout eastern to central United States, but can also be seen in western states such as California. They can grow in many habitats including woodlands, meadows, or along rivers, and are sometimes considered weeds because of their adaptability.

description: Sorry for only vague ID
Sorry for only vague ID

Deltoid leaves, glabrous spur petals, lighter purple flowers. The sepals appear eciliate. Flora of the Chicago indicates that this species has ciliolate sepals, although Flora of North America lists it as either ciliate or eciliate.

These plants were seen in mesic or wet-mesic dolomite prairie. I can't find any mention of this plant occuring in such habitats, but I have seen it mentioned that it occurs on rocky bluffs. Perhaps it tends to be restricted to slightly shadier habitats because it doesn't compete as well in the dense growth of typical prairies. The harsher conditions of a dolomite prairie, on the other hand, may give V. missouriensis enough of an advantage to persist. Alternatively, these plants may have persisted following succession to a more closed canopy and subsequent brush removal.
